Bit Selection and Detection Functions

These built-in functions operate on arbitrary-width binary values and are useful for priority selection, interrupt handling, one-hot encoding, bit scanning, masking, and state decoding.

---

HIGH()

Returns the highest (most significant) bit that is set to "1".

All other bits become "0".

Syntax

HIGH(Xbit value)

Returns

Xbit

Same width as the input.

Examples

HIGH(00101010)

Result:

00100000

---

HIGH(00010000)

Result:

00010000

---

HIGH(00000000)

Result:

00000000

---

Typical Uses

Interrupt priority selection
Highest-priority request detection
Bus arbitration
First-active source selection

---

LOW()

Returns the lowest (least significant) bit that is set to "1".

All other bits become "0".

Syntax

LOW(Xbit value)

Returns

Xbit

Same width as the input.

Examples

LOW(00101010)

Result:

00000010

---

LOW(00010000)

Result:

00010000

---

LOW(00000000)

Result:

00000000

---

Typical Uses

Lowest-priority request selection
Round-robin allocators
Bit scanning
Resource assignment

---

ANY()

Returns whether any bit is set.

Syntax

ANY(Xbit value)

Returns

1bit

Examples

ANY(00000000)

Result:

0

---

ANY(00010000)

Result:

1

---

ANY(00101010)

Result:

1

---

Equivalent Logic

OR(all bits)

---

Typical Uses

Interrupt pending detection
Queue not empty
At least one key pressed
Error detection

---

ZERO()

Returns whether all bits are zero.

Syntax

ZERO(Xbit value)

Returns

1bit

Examples

ZERO(00000000)

Result:

1

---

ZERO(00010000)

Result:

0

---

ZERO(00101010)

Result:

0

---

Equivalent Logic

NOT(ANY(value))

---

Typical Uses

Zero flag generation
CPU comparisons
Counter completion tests
Empty-state detection

---

BITINDEX()

Returns the index of the active bit.

The input is typically expected to contain exactly one bit set ("one-hot" value).

Bit numbering starts at "0" from the least significant bit.

Syntax

BITINDEX(Xbit value)

Returns

log2(X) bits

Examples

BITINDEX(00000001)

Result:

000

---

BITINDEX(00000100)

Result:

010

---

BITINDEX(00100000)

Result:

101

---

Typical Uses

Priority encoder construction
Interrupt vector generation
One-hot decoding reversal
Address selection

---

Example

8wire requests = 00101010

8wire selected = HIGH(requests)

3wire irq =
BITINDEX(selected)

Result:

selected = 00100000
irq      = 101

---

ONEHOT()

Converts a binary index into a one-hot value.

The output contains exactly one bit set to "1".

Bit position equals the supplied index.

Syntax

ONEHOT(Xbit index)

Returns

2^X bits

Examples

ONEHOT(000)

Result:

00000001

---

ONEHOT(001)

Result:

00000010

---

ONEHOT(010)

Result:

00000100

---

ONEHOT(101)

Result:

00100000

---

ONEHOT(111)

Result:

10000000

---

Typical Uses

Address decoding
State decoding
Memory bank selection
Peripheral enables
Instruction decoding

---

BITINDEX() and ONEHOT()

These functions are inverses of each other.

BITINDEX(
  ONEHOT(x)
)

returns:

x

Example:

BITINDEX(
  ONEHOT(101)
)

Result:

101

---

Building a Priority Encoder

A dedicated priority encoder function is usually unnecessary.

Example:

8wire requests = 00101010

8wire winner =
HIGH(requests)

1wire valid =
ANY(requests)

3wire index =
BITINDEX(winner)

Result:

winner = 00100000
valid  = 1
index  = 101

This provides the same information as a traditional priority encoder while keeping the primitives reusable for many other applications.





